## The Value of Sentinel Lymph Node Mapping for the Staging of Node-Negative Colon Cancer

## Propensity Score and Mediation Analyses

Benjamin/uni00A0Weixler, MD,* Michaela/uni00A0Ramser, MD, MBA,† Rene/uni00A0Warschkow, MD, MSc,‡§ Carsten T./uni00A0Viehl, MD, /uni2225 Peter G./uni00A0Vaughan-Shaw, MD,¶ Andreas/uni00A0Zettl, MD, # Christoph/uni00A0Kettelhack, MD,** and Markus/uni00A0Zuber, MD†**

Objectives: Mediation analysis to assess the protective impact of sentinel lymph node (SLN) mapping on prognosis and survival of patients with colon cancer through a more precise evaluation of the lymph node (LN) status.

Background: Up to 20% of patients with node-negative colon cancer develop disease recurrence. Conventional histopathological LN examination may be limited in describing the real metastatic burden of LN.

Methods: Data of 312 patients with stage I & II colon cancer was collected prospectively. Patients were either staged using intraoperative SLN mapping with multilevel sectioning and immunohistochemical staining of the SLN or conventional techniques. The value of the SLN mapping for the detection of truly node-negative patients was assessed using Cox regression and mediation analysis.

Results: SLN mapping was performed in 143 patients. Disease recurrence was observed in 13 (9.1%) patients staged with SLN mapping and in 27 (16%) staged conventionally. Five-year overall survival (OS) rate was 82.7% (95% confidence interval [CI], 76.589.4%) with SLN mapping compared with 65.8% (95% CI, 58.8-73.7%). Five-year cancer-specific survival (CSS) was 95.1% (95% CI, 91.3-99.0%) with SLN mapping compared with 92.5% (95% CI, 88.0-97.2%). Node-negative staging with SLN mapping was associated with significantly better OS (hazard ratio [HR], 0.64; 95% CI, 0.56-0.72; P < 0.001) and CSS (HR, 0.49; 95% CI, 0.390.61; P < 0.001) in multivariate analysis. Mediation analysis confirmed a direct protective effect of SLN mapping on OS (HR, 0.78; 95% CI, 0.52-0.96; P < 0.01) and disease-free survival (DFS) (HR, 0.75; 95% CI, 0.48-0.89; P < 0.01).

Conclusions: Staging performed by SLN mapping with multilevel sectioning provides more accurate results than conventional staging. The observed clinically relevant and statistically significant benefit in OS and DFS is explained by a more accurate detection of positive LN by SLN mapping.

Keywords: cancer-specific survival, colon cancer, mediation analysis, overall survival, propensity score analysis, sentinel lymph node

## INTRODUCTION

Standard treatment for patients with nonmetastasized colon cancer  involves  surgical  resection  according  to  oncological

The survival bene/fit from adjuvant chemotherapy in  patients  with  node-positive  disease  is  widely  established, yet there remains considerable debate surrounding the extent and the principles of oncological surgery, for example, central vascular ligation. 1,2 Despite advantages in oncological treatment regimens and a greater and better surgical awareness of correct anatomical planes, patients with node-negative colon cancer still develop disease recurrences overall in 20% of the cases. 3-5 According to current oncological treatment standards, node-negative patients without risk factors do not qualify for any adjuvant therapy. Thus, suggesting the assumption that they are generally believed to be tumor free and therefore should not suffer from disease recurrence. The situation is different in stage III colon cancer, where clinically occult systemic small tumor in/filtrates are present in a signi/ficant proportion of patients. 6

Lymph node (LN) involvement is one of the most important prognostic factors in patients with colon cancer and a high LN yield is therefore essential for correct staging. Therefore, accurate staging is directly dependent on the histological analysis of the mesocolon, including the LN harvest and LN involvement. Small tumor deposits may be easily missed, leading to understaging and a higher risk of disease recurrence. 7-10 Sentinel LN (SLN) mapping would allow the identi/fication of LN with the highest probability of harboring metastases and directed histological analysis to ensure accurate LN staging as previously shown in some seminal publications on the subject. 11-18 We have previously shown that SLN mapping with intensive histopathological workup detects isolated tumor cells and micrometastases in up to 25% of patients with node-negative colon cancer, resulting in a signi/ficant stage migration and impact on survival. 7,10,16,19

These data suggest that the high recurrence rate in patients with colon cancer reported to be node negative may in fact have had occult nodal disease that could have indicated an advanced and possibly already systemic disease. The aim of the current study was to investigate the value of the SLN mapping with intensive histopathological workup in patients with reported LN negative colon cancer.

## METHODS

## Study Settings

A retrospective comparative cohort study was performed at 2  university-af/filiated  hospitals  in  Switzerland  (University Hospital Basel, Cantonal Hospital Olten). Patients from a prospective trial and a prospectively maintained database were considered for this analysis from May 2000 to December 2014. The former are patients that were operated for colon cancer from May 2000 to December 2006 and were included in a prospective multicenter (Olten and Basel) cohort study (NCT00826579), designed  to  assess  LN  staging  with  SLN  mapping. 16 From January 2007, patients treated in the Cantonal Hospital Olten were staged using intraoperative SLN mapping routinely, while at the University Hospital Basel patients underwent standard oncologic resection and conventional postoperative histological analysis. Follow-up data were completed until March 2018 (median follow-up of 68.2 months).

All patients underwent standard segmental oncological colectomy by open or laparoscopic approach. Procedures in Olten were performed by a single surgeon who has been trained in Basel as well, suggesting the same approach to surgical oncology as surgeons in Basel. Procedures in Basel were performed by a well-trained and dedicated team of visceral surgeons.

Patients with pT1-T4a colon cancer and staged by conventional nodal assessment as only node negative (pN0) were included. Patients with locally invasive (T4b) and node-positive cancer, and those with distant metastases were excluded. Patients with prior abdominal cancer surgery and those with age <18 years were also excluded. Ethical approval was granted and written informed consent was obtained from all patients.

The SLN mapping has been described in detail elsewhere. 16,20 Brie/fly, isosulfan blue was injected into the subserosa around the tumor /first in vivo as part of the previously mentioned study and was thereafter continued as standard procedure ex-vivo in the Cantonal Hospital Olten. 16 LN staining blue within 10 minutes after dye application were marked with a suture and collected as SLN and then processed according to our previously reported protocol. 16 The protocol consists of 5 serial sections of each SLN that were obtained at 3 different representative levels. The /first section of each level was stained with hematoxylin and eosin (H&E). If no metastatic deposits were detectable by H&E, the fourth section of each level was immunostained with the pancytokeratin marker AE1/AE3 (DakoCytomation, Glostrup, Denmark).

All patients were discussed at a multidisciplinary tumor conference and adjuvant chemotherapy recommended to stage II patients featuring high-risk factors (ie, <12 LN analyzed, T4a tumor, lymphovascular or perineural invasion, poorly differentiated  histology  or  tumor  perforation). 21 Follow-up  was performed  according  to  the  national  surveillance  guidelines for patients after curative colon cancer resection. 22 For reporting consistency in the current article, all tumors were restaged retrospectively in 2018 according to the 7th version of the tumor-node-metastasis classi/fication system. 23

## Statistical Analyses

Statistical  analyses  were  performed  using  the  R  statistical software (www.r-project.org). A 2-sided P value <0.05 was considered  statistically  signi/ficant.  Continuous  data  are

expressed as means and SD. Categorical data and proportions were compared using χ 2 test and conventional t test or MannWhitney U tests as appropriate for continuous data. Missing data for body mass index (BMI) and American Society of Anesthesiologist (ASA) score here as it is the /first mention of the abbreviation. score were imputed using the random survival forest method. 24 The value of SLN mapping as putative prognostic factor on survival was assessed by univariate and thereafter multivariable Cox regression, adjusting for gender, age, BMI, ASA score, tumor localization, Union Internationale Contre le Cancer (UICC) stage, tumor grading (dichotomized in G1/2 vs G3/4), LN harvest, adjuvant therapy use, and year of operation (risk set). The Cox regression models included the center as a cluster term to adjust for center effects. The variance was estimated by robust sandwich variance estimators. P values and con/fidence intervals (CI) were estimated using the Wald method.

To further assess the impact of SLN on survival, a propensity score analysis was performed to better adjust for the potential baseline confounding variables (risk set). 25-27 The 'Matching' R package was used to perform a bipartite weighting propensity score analysis (full matching). 28,29 The baseline risk pro/files of the matched patients were /finally compared by logistic regression (conditional on SLN mapping) to assure that no major differences in observed baseline patients characteristics persisted. The proportional hazard assumption was tested by scaled Schoenfeld residuals using the 'cox.zph' function and by inspection of the hazard ratio (HR) plots. The prognostic value of SLN mapping for the survival outcomes was /finally assessed in a strati/fied Cox regression analysis applying the subclasses and the weights obtained by the propensity score analysis and center as a cluster term.

Finally, mediation analyses were performed to further assess the effect of SLN mapping on survival. Age and year were included as continuous variables and stage as a dichotomized variable (as stage I vs II). Mediation analyses were performed using the 'mma' R package implementing the model proposed by Yu et al. 30,31 Mediators are referred to as variables that explain the observed relationship between the exposure variable SLN mapping and the survival outcomes. The association between SLN mapping and the other predictor variables was modeled by multivariate additive regression trees with a Bernoulli distribution to deal with nonlinear relationships, hierarchical data structures, and a mixture of quantitative and qualitative variables. Estimates with 95% CI are given.

## RESULTS

A total of 312 patients were included. Staging with intraoperative SLN mapping was performed in 143 patients (45.8%). Patients with SLN mapping had a lower ASA stage and were younger. The SLN mapping group had a signi/ficant higher LN harvest, were more likely to receive adjuvant chemotherapy and demonstrated improved outcomes, with less local recurrence and death (Table/uni00A01).

## Survival Analysis

On  univariate  analysis,  SLN  mapping  was  associated  with improved overall survival (OS) (HR, 0.59; 95% CI, 0.44-0.80; P < 0.001), cancer-speci/fic survival (CSS) (HR, 0.72; 95% CI, 0.58-0.88; P < 0.001), disease-free survival (DFS) (HR, 0.56; 95% CI, 0.44-0.71; P < 0.001), and relapse- and tumor deathfree survival (RFS) (HR, 0.51; 95% CI, 0.48-0.54, P < 0.001). After strati/fication into stage I & II disease SLN mapping persisted to be associated with improved OS in stage I (HR, 0.81; 95% CI, 0.69-0.95; P = 0.009) and II (HR, 0.51; 95% CI, 0.350.73; P < 0.001) (Fig./uni00A01). In DFS, SLN mapping was associated with an improved outcome both in stage I (HR, 0.79; 95% CI, 0.710.88; P < 0.001) and stage II disease (HR, 0.47; 95% CI, 0.360.62; P < 0.001) (Fig./uni00A01) as well as in RFS in stage I (HR, 0.51; 95% CI, 0.43-0.61; P < 0.001) and stage II (HR, 0.51; 95% CI, 0.48-0.54; P < 0.001).

Overall 5-year survival was 65.8% (58.8-73.7%) in those who underwent conventional staging and 82.7% (76.5-89.4%) in those who underwent staging with SLN mapping (HR, 0.59; 95% CI, 0.44-0.80; P < 0.001). Five-year CSS and DFS was also greater in those who underwent staging with SLN mapping (CSS 92.5% vs 95.1; DFS 60.8% vs 79.7%).

The survival association with SLN mapping remained after adjustment for other relevant factors using multivariate analysis, with improved OS (HR, 0.64; 95% CI, 0.56-0.72; P < 0.001), CSS (HR, 0.49; 95% CI, 0.39-0.61; P < 0.001), DFS (HR, 0.57; 95% CI, 0.48-0.68; P < 0.001), and RFS (HR, 0.30; 95% CI, 0.22-0.40; P < 0.001) (Table/uni00A02).

## Propensity Score Analysis

Before the matching procedure, the propensity score for patients with  no  SLN  mapping  was  0.389  ±  0.177  compared  with 0.540 ± 0.177 in patients with SLN mapping ( P < 0.001), thus

indicating a strong bias regarding the patient characteristics in the 2 groups. After the matching procedure, the propensity score was virtually the same in the 2 patient groups (0.533 ± 0.173 for patients with no SLN mapping compared with 0.532 ± 0.171 for patients with SLN mapping [ P = 0.989]), thus indicating no persisting bias regarding the observed patient characteristics in the 2 groups. When performing the propensity score matching procedure, 2 patients with no SLN mapping and 3 patients with SLN mapping could not be matched with patients from the other group. These patients had to be excluded because there was no counterpart in the other group matching their characteristics. Five-year OS rate after propensity score matching was 75% (95% CI, 68.8-81.7%) for conventionally staged patients and 80.7% (95% CI, 74.9-86.9%) for patients staged with SLN mapping (HR for SLN mapping, 0.75; 95% CI, 0.65-0.86; P < 0.001).

Five-year CSS was 91% (95% CI, 86.5-95.8%) for conventionally staged patients and 96.5% (95% CI, 93.7-99.4%) for staging with SLN mapping (HR for SLN mapping, 0.38; 95% CI, 0.37-0.38; P < 0.001).

Five-year DFS was for conventionally staged patients 72% (95% CI, 65.6-79.0%) and 78.6% (95% CI, 72.6-85.1%) for staging with SLN mapping (HR for SLN mapping, 0.73; 95% CI, 0.68-0.78; P < 0.001).

The direct effect of SLN mapping on survival was estimated with a HR = 0.78 (95% CI, 0.52-0.96) and the indirect effect of other variables (ie, age, year of diagnosis, sex, BMI, tumor stage, tumor grade, LN harvest, adjuvant therapy, and tumor site) was estimated with a HR = 0.85 (95% CI, 0.611.07). In relative terms, the direct effect was 60.2% and the indirect effect was 39.8% of the total effect. Age was the most prominent indirect effect (37.2% of the total effect). Mediation analysis also con/firmed SLN mapping as signi/ficantly protective for DFS with a total effect of HR = 0.66 (95% CI, 0.38-0.87; P < 0.01). The direct and indirect effects were estimated with HR = 0.75 (95% CI, 0.48-0.89) and HR = 0.88 (95% CI, 0.661.09). In relative terms, the direct effect was 69.5% and the indirect effect 30.5%.

## DISCUSSION

Accurate LN staging in colon cancer still presents a considerable challenge, evidenced by the high rate of recurrences in patients with node-negative disease. 2-4 This study assessed the value of the SLN mapping with multilevel sectioning and immunohistochemical staining for the staging of node-negative colon cancer by means of propensity score and mediation analyses. Our results demonstrate that node-negative staging according to the SLN mapping protocol was associated with a markedly improved OS, CSS, and DFS compared with staging with conventional histopathological workup.

Conventional LN staging is traditionally performed using 1-2 H&E stained sections of each detected LN. This worldwide standard inherits the considerable risk that nodal tumor deposits  are  missed  and  patients  will  be  understaged.  The importance of LN harvest, understaging and stage migration is widely established in the literature. 15,18,32,33 While both LN harvest and patient survival have increased over the past 2 decades, the proportion of patients with stage III disease has remained static. 34-36 In this respect, some authors questioned if understaging and stage migration exists at all, arguing that if a higher number of resected LN would lead to a more precise staging, the incidence rate of stage III patients would consequently increase in relation to node-negative patients. Such an argument ignores the fact that survival rates of patients with stage I and II disease would not change as more negative nodes are harvested and assessed as there is no clear bene/fit from a higher LN yield in true node-negative patients. However, even in studies that view stage migration critically, survival is greater as LN harvest increases in patients with node-negative colon cancer, and suggests that the observed effect is best explained by means of more accurate LN staging, which clearly speaks for stage migration. 34 It seems very plausible that a combination of factors like consequent resection of metastases in LN and a more accurate staging contribute to the improvements in survival. In the current study, we have shown that SLN mapping has a direct association both on OS and DFS and was in fact the single most important prognostic factor for survival. To our knowledge, this is the /first study to use a mediation analysis to identify single factors relevant to survival in patients with node-negative colon cancer.

The advantage of the SLN mapping with multilevel sectioning is that the LN with the highest probability to harbor metastases will undergo in-depth analysis. This reduces the risk that micrometastases (0.2-2 mm in diameter) that are considered as 'positive' 37 and small metastases will be missed, with subsequent understaging, under treatment and increased risk of disease recurrence. Our previous work has shown that SLN mapping  with  multilevel  sectioning  will  lead  to  an  upstaging in 15.4-31.1% of patients, otherwise classi/fied as node negative. 7,16,38

Complete mesocolic excision (CME) in accordance with the oncological principals of total mesorectal excision has gained widespread interest in recent years. 39,40 Despite initial enthusiasm, the evidence for a survival bene/fit in stage I & II colon cancer is inconsistent. 41-43 Furthermore, methodological concerns limit the conclusions that can be drawn. A recent study reported a reduced risk for recurrence after CME for right-sided colon cancer, 44 yet it was a retrospective study based across different centers, with only 1 center performing CME. There was also a signi/ficant treatment effect of CME on stage I & II colon cancer suggesting relevant understaging in this subgroup of patients. 42 In a/uni00A0 recent nonrandomized study comparing CME and nonCME cases, no differences in 3-year OS and DFS, although recurrence-free survival was greater after CME in stage II and III patients but not stage I patients. 45 However, locoregional recurrence in LN negative colon cancer is reported to be as low as 2% within 5 years after operation. 39,46 Therefore, the question arises to what extent these results are important for node-negative patients, especially as extended surgical resection seems to be associated with increased morbidity that may impact overall outcomes. 43,47

Given that the current rate of disease recurrence after colon cancer resection are unacceptably high and strong data to justify extended surgical resection in stage I & II colon cancer is missing, SLN mapping offers a convincing, easy, and safe way to improve LN staging. We argue of a more in-depth analysis of speci/fic LN in a specimen of a standard and according to surgical oncological principals conducted colon resections. It seems inappropriate to harvest more and more LN with CME without improving the technique of pathological workup or at least focused in-depth analysis of the LN bearing the highest chance of harboring metastases. We are therefore convinced that the results of our study support the true value of SLN mapping: it is an independent factor improving OS, CSS, and DFS as it incorporates a more thorough examination of the specimen that results in a higher number of retrieved and analyzed LN, upstaging and therefore a more accurate overall staging.

We would like to acknowledge the limitations of our study. The main shortcoming of this analysis is the retrospective cohort study design. In contrast to a randomized trial, the existence of confounders cannot be ruled out. However, the observed survival bene/fit after SLN mapping was uniformly con/firmed by adjustment with conventional multivariable analysis, propensity score matching, and mediation analysis making a clinically relevant selection bias unlikely. The inclusion of patients from 2 centers makes on the side slight differences in treatment or multidisciplinary tumor decisions regarding adjuvant therapy possible, on the other side, it guarantees a wider generalizability of our results for other surgeons. All participating surgeons have received their training at the University Hospital Basel and therefore represent the same approach and understanding to surgical oncology. Nevertheless, there might have occurred slight changes in surgical techniques over the years. The SLN procedure was predominantly performed at one of the participating centers, and there mainly by 1 single surgeon whose SLN detection rates prove the excellence in technique and expertise in the /field and demonstrate what bene/fits can be derived from a pro/ficient level of experience in the technique. At the time of patient inclusion, genetic testing was not a standard procedure, and we therefore cannot report on these data.

## CONCLUSIONS

The results of this study clearly demonstrate that SLN mapping with multilevel sectioning supports the aim of more accurately identifying patients that are truly LN negative. Even with extended resections with CME but standard histopathological LN analysis, there is a potential risk of understaging and extended dissection may not be justi/fied in node-negative

patients. SLN mapping provides a greater indication of LN involvement  when  compared  with  conventional  histological analysis, and thus ensures that patients are accurately staged. Critically, in the current study, we demonstrate a strong association between SLN mapping and survival outcomes, which clearly supports the use of SLN in the staging of colon cancer.
